VA s part of the month-long Thiruppavai fest in the month of Dhanurmasam, Sri Desika Sabha organised a discourse by Tirumalai Ananthan Pillai of Srirangam and vocal concerts by Vasundara Rajagopalan of Chennai and S. Padmavathi of the city.Vasundara, a disciple of N. Gopala Iyer, sang numbers on Lord Ranganatha as well as &#8216;Thiruppavai pasurams' which were very well presented in the company of Dinakar on the violin and Aravind on the mridangam. . Malayamarutham was taken for an elegant expansion bringing out the nuances of the raga for Thyagaraja's Dhanyudevvadu with crisp swarakalpana. The contribution by the violinist added lustre to the concert and the mridangam player also did well with his enchanting tani in Adi. She presented the pallavi with neraval and swarakalpana going in an ascending and descending order which shows her maturity and knowledge. On the whole the concert reflected a traditional approach and was neatly presented with a good team work.Scholarly recitalPadmavathi presented a concert consisting of melody as well as rich manodharma sangeetham. She too was accompanied on the violin by Dinakar and her brother Aravind on the mridangam. She began her concert with a melodious Sahana Varnam Karunimpave in Adi. A slokam in Nayakee followed by Sri Ranga Nayakam in the same ragam was maturely rendered. Thiruppavai 12th pasuram Kannaithillam in the ragam Kedaragowla was presented with classicism. Suddha Danyasi was detailed for an aesthetical ragam for Sri Hari Vallabhe in Adi with neat swaram in it. Padmavathi did very well to maintain the ragam essence and the expression which she brought out was commendable.
